    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about muscle growth and saw two different terms: mechanical tension and metabolic stress. can u explain the difference between them and which one is more important for hypertrophy?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Mechanical tension and metabolic stress are two primary drivers of muscle growth, but they represent different stimuli. Mechanical tension is the physical pulling force placed on the muscle fibers during resistance training, which causes microscopic damage. Metabolic stress relates to the accumulation of byproducts like lactate in the muscle during intense, high-volume workouts. While both contribute, most research suggests that maximizing mechanical tension, often through heavy weights, is the most crucial factor for inducing significant hypertrophy.",
      "source": "target",
