    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if i'm focusing on mechanical tension, how exactly does that tension actually cause the muscle to grow? like what's happening at the cellular or fiber level when those forces are applied?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When high mechanical tension is applied, the muscle fibers experience mechanical strain, which signals a need for adaptation. This strain activates various mechanoreceptors within the muscle tissue. In response, the body initiates signaling pathways that promote satellite cell activation and subsequent muscle protein synthesis. Essentially, the tension acts as a stressor that forces the muscle to repair itself stronger and larger to handle future loads.",
      "source": "target",
