    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "can u go into more detail on what those mechanoreceptors are doing? like is there some sort of tiny physical process or microscopic \"work\" happening inside the cell to convert that tension into a signal?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Mechanoreceptors are specialized sensors, like those found in tendons and muscle fascia, that detect physical deformation or strain. When tension pulls on these structures, it causes a conformational change in the receptor proteins. This physical change is transduced into an electrochemical signal—a nerve impulse—that travels to the central nervous system. This signal is the \"work\" that converts the physical force into a biochemical signal, triggering the growth cascade.",
      "source": "target",
